, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Herbert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German, English, and French: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. In Britain, this Old French name, introduced by the Normans, reinforced the less common Old English cognate <i>Herebeorht</i>. The surname was taken to Ireland after the Anglo-Norman invasion and in the 16th century.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the German personal name (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Harbison","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): patronymic from the Older Scots and Middle English personal name   Herbert   (the change from <i>-er-</i> to <i>-ar-</i> was a common one in Old French and Middle English). An intrusive <i>n</i> later gave   Harbinson  ."]},{"name":"Hebard","meanings":["English (Surrey):","variant of   Herbert  , with assimilation of the first <i>r</i>. Compare   Hebb  .","variant of   Hibbert  ."]},{"name":"Harbert","meanings":["German and English: variant of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herbers","meanings":["German and Dutch: patronymic from   Herbert  . It is found mainly in Lower Saxony and across the Dutch border."]},{"name":"Dickherber","meanings":["Probably a nickname for a fat person by the name of   Herbert  , of which <i>Herber</i> is a short form, or, more likely, in the north from <b>Die(c)kherber</b>, a topographic and distinguishing name for a <i>Herber</i> living by the dike, see   Dicke   2. Compare   Dickmeyer  ."]},{"name":"Hebert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Emile, Normand, Jacques, Marcel, Pierre, Lucien, Michel, Gaston, Alcide, Camille.","French (<b>Hébert</b>): assimilated form of   Herbert  . Compare   Abair  ,   Abar  ,   Abare  ,   Abear  ,   Aber  ,   Eber  , and   Ebert  .","German: variant of   Heber   1."]},{"name":"Herber","meanings":["German and Dutch: variant of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herbertson","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): patronymic from the Older Scots and Middle English personal name   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Hebb","meanings":["English (East Yorkshire and northeast Midlands): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hebb</i>, <i>Ebb</i>, pet forms of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herb","meanings":["South German: nickname for a harsh or rough person, from Middle High German <i>herb</i> ‘tart, harsh’.","German: from the personal name <i>Herpo</i>, a pet form of   Herbert  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Cynarth ap Herbert was born about 1164, in Glamorgan, Wales. He had at least 1 daughter with Unknown."},"et":{"about 1164–":"umbes 1164–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1190–1281":"1190–1281","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1190":"1190","abt 1190":"umbes 1190","1164":"1164","1281":"1281","about 1164":"umbes 1164","Miskin, Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1164–":"noin 1164–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1190–1281":"1190–1281","1164–Male":"1164–Kuollut","1190":"1190","abt 1190":"noin 1190","1164":"1164","1281":"1281","about 1164":"noin 1164","Miskin, Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1164–":"environ 1164–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1190–1281":"1190–1281","1164–Male":"1164–Décédé","1190":"1190","abt 1190":"environ 1190","1164":"1164","1281":"1281","about 1164":"environ 1164","Miskin, Glamorga